  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potentially longer sentences if linked to other criminal activities\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in laundering\n- Fines can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific criminal statutes violated\n- Whether the offense involved other criminal activities\n- Individual's criminal history\n\nThese penalties are typically prosecuted under federal statutes like:\n- The Money Laundering Control Act\n- Bank Secrecy Act\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations (RICO) Act\n\nIt's important to note that money laundering is a serious federal crime with severe potential consequences. Actual penalties can vary based on specific circumstances and prosecutorial discretion.",
